title: Act4_Decisions_SpendTime_SliceofLife
---
<<set_route YarnManager Decisions_SpendTime_SliceofLife>>
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: I’m fine with something relaxing.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Good choice. This one’s great.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]The movie opens on a small apartment at dawn.[/i]
: [i]A young man, Ren, is trying to get his little sister ready for school while packing breakfast, sorting bills, and answering a call from work.[/i]
: [i]He burns toast, steps on a toy, and insists everything is “completely under control” while the smoke alarm goes off.[/i]
: [i]On the way to school, his sister complains about her hair. Ren tries to fix it, makes it worse...[/i]
: [i]...then offers to buy her a “good morning memory” from a kiosk to make up for it.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: That’s a thing?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Small memories, mostly. Mood boosters. People buy confidence before interviews, calming memories before exams...
Eve: There are even first-date packages, which are apparently terrible.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Apparently?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: I’ve never bought one. Obviously.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: I wasn’t accusing you.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Good, because if I did, I’d at least buy the premium version.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]Ren sees the price and quietly puts his wallet away. Instead, he tells his sister a ridiculous story about a heroic pigeon stealing the mayor’s sandwich.[/i]
: [i]She laughs and forgets she was upset.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Ren’s basically raising her alone. That’s why he worries over tiny things.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Your dad is like that?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Yeah. He acts relaxed, but he notices everything. If I cough once, he asks if I need medicine. If I’m five minutes late, he “just happens” to be outside.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: He must care about you a lot.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: He does. Sometimes I think he cares so much because he already lost too much.
Eve: When someone is all you have left, maybe you stop asking questions that might take them away.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: ...I can understand that.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]On-screen, Ren’s sister auditions for a school commercial.[/i]
: [i]The teacher says they want “authentic childhood joy,” then hands the children a list of approved expressions and memories to rehearse.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Even commercials use planted memories?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Of course. Manufactured celebrities are all memory design. Agencies decide what people should remember about you.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: What about Hunters?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Definitely. If you became an agency Hunter, they’d probably make you the “silent protector of the forgotten city.” Lots of shots of you standing in the rain.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: That sounds inconvenient.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: That’s your reaction?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: I don’t like standing in the rain.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Wow. The legend collapses immediately.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Could rivals sabotage that?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: All the time. Leak the wrong memory, pay witnesses to remember you badly, make people associate you with cowardice or cruelty.
Eve: If enough people remember a version of you, it starts to matter more than what actually happened.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]In the movie, Ren’s sister refuses the commercial because she doesn’t want strangers told how to love her.[/i]
: [i]She says she’d rather be remembered properly by her brother.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: This is one of my favorite scenes. Being loved by one person can still count, even if the whole world doesn’t know you.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]Later, Ren takes a second job delivering memory cartridges and misses his sister’s recital. He arrives just as it ends.[/i]
: [i]Instead of making excuses, he apologizes, and they sit outside eating convenience-store buns.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: That’s what I like about family stories. Even when people mess up, there’s still this understanding underneath it.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Were you close with your dad right away?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: I was awkward. I wanted to help with everything, but I was terrible at it. Once I tried to make breakfast and somehow made poison.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: That’s... impressive.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Another time, I was taking orders and wrote down everything the client said. Including “uh,” “actually,” and “wait, no, not that one.”
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: At least you were thorough.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Dad laughed so hard he had to go into the back room. I was furious for three days.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Only three?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: What can I say? I’m very forgiving.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]The movie ends with Ren and his sister in a slightly better apartment. He makes breakfast without burning it.[/i]
: [i]When she asks if they’ll be okay, he says, “As long as we’re together.”[/i]
: [i]The screen fades out.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: So? How was it?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Simple, but not shallow. The ending is a little unrealistic, though. People don’t always get rewarded for trying hard.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: That’s fair. But sometimes I want a story to be kinder than reality. A happily ever after.
===


title: Act4_Decisions_SpendTime_MurderMystery
---
<<set_route YarnManager Decisions_SpendTime_MurderMystery>>
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Maybe the murder mystery. The family conflict sounds interesting.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Good choice. It’s more family drama than murder, honestly, but I think that’s why I like it.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]The movie opens with a detective arriving at a seaside estate in the rain.[/i]
: [i]A member of the Veyne family, an old political dynasty, has been found dead. Every relative has a motive.[/i]
: [i]The detective walks past campaign posters, old portraits, and a childhood photo of the siblings standing at the beach, holding small Arcana charms.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: What are those charms?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Arcana symbols. Kids get them as gifts sometimes, but in the movie they’re also a hint.
Eve: The ambitious brother has the Emperor, the sister who keeps running away has the Fool, things like that.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Do people usually show their Arcana that openly?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Not their real one. That’s private.
Eve: Arcana are tied to memories, so people get weird about them. Some act like it decides your whole personality before you even speak.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Does it?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: I think it influences people. But deciding someone’s entire life from one symbol sounds... cruel.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]The movie continues. The family gathers for dinner after the funeral. At first, they pretend to be polite, but the conversation quickly breaks down.[/i]
: [i]One brother accuses the others of using the victim’s death for political leverage. Another says the family was already dead long before the murder.[/i]
: [i]Their father begs them to stop, but no one listens.[/i]
: [i]On-screen, one sibling slams a glass down and says the only thing the family ever shared was a last name.[/i]
: [i]Another laughs and says childhood memories are only valuable because they can be sold.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: ...
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]The argument worsens. Someone brings up the old beach memory, the last recording of all the siblings happy together.[/i]
: [i]One wants to sell it to pay campaign debts. Another wants to destroy it because it makes them look weak.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: That’s awful.
Eve: Sorry, I don’t know why this part always gets to me.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: You don’t have to apologize.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: I just don’t understand how they can throw it away like that. I know families fight. I know people hurt each other.
Eve: But to have proof that you were happy together once, and still treat it like an asset or a weapon...
Eve: Some people would give anything to have that.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]On-screen, the detective finds the childhood memory recording.[/i]
: [i]The siblings are children at the ocean, building a crooked sandcastle and arguing over who gets to be “ruler of the sea.”[/i]
: [i]Their mother laughs and tells them family should be the place they return to, not the thing they conquer.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: I’ve never seen the real sea.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: You want to?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: More than anything. I always thought... if I ever went, I’d want to go with family.
Eve: Otherwise it would feel like arriving somewhere beautiful and having no one to turn to.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]The movie returns to the present. The detective reveals that the victim had been trying to buy back the beach memory before dying.[/i]
: [i]The family argues again, but this time the anger feels weaker, exhausted.[/i]
: [i]The mystery remains partly unresolved; no one can agree on what really happened that night.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: So the detective doesn’t solve it?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Not completely. He figures out the crime, but not the family. I think that’s the point.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]The final scene shows the surviving family members standing on the beach at dawn. They don’t reconcile. The old memory is something they can’t return to.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: So? What did you think?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: It was sad. I expected the mystery to have a cleaner answer.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Same, the first time I watched it. But now I appreciate the nuance. Sometimes there isn’t a neat way to fix it.
Eve: But even if they couldn’t go back to being that family, that memory still existed.
===


title: Act4_Decisions_SpendTime_Romcom
---
<<set_route YarnManager Decisions_SpendTime_Romcom>>
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: I guess we could try the new one.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Really? I didn’t take you for a romcom person.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: You said it was new, and you seemed familiar with the studio.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: I wouldn’t say familiar.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: How many of their movies have you watched?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Maybe ten. Or twenty. Anyway, sit down before you start interrogating me.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]The movie opens in the city, where Margaret, an overworked memory-copywriter, is writing an outrage campaign for a corporation.[/i]
: [i]Her mother calls, asking her to come home and help with the family shop.[/i]
: [i]On-screen, Margaret insists she’s too busy. Her mother gently says they haven’t seen her in months.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: I already don’t understand her. I get being busy, but if your family is calling because they miss you, shouldn’t that matter?
Eve: Sorry. I know it’s just a movie. I just think people should treasure family more when they have one.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: What would you do?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Go home immediately. Probably overpack, panic, and bring Dad a gift he didn’t ask for. What about you?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Well, I don’t even know if I have a family. Memory loss, remember?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Oh. Right. Well... Dad would definitely let you join us for dinner if you wanted. He pretends he doesn’t collect strays, but he absolutely does.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: I’ll keep that in mind.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]Margaret returns to her hometown, Lumas. She helps a customer repair a hunting rifle.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: No, no, no. Absolutely not.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Something wrong?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Everything. You don’t put the cartridge in before checking the Fate channel.
Eve: Also, why is she hitting the barrel? That does nothing except make the weapon worse and maybe louder.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Are these movies usually inaccurate?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Yes, but this is personal now.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]The door chimes. A handsome Hunter named Krys enters, wounded but charming. Margaret immediately forgets how to speak.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: She repairs weapons for a living, but one attractive Hunter walks in and she loses all motor function?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: That’s the romcom contract. Someone has to become embarrassed within the first twenty minutes.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]The movie cuts through a montage of awkward flirting. Krys buys unnecessary supplies just to talk to Margaret. Margaret pretends not to notice.[/i]
: [i]Eventually, Krys reveals his tragic backstory: a memory monster destroyed his home after false humans infiltrated the district.[/i]
: [i]He vows to hunt both monsters and false humans until the world is safe.[/i]
: [i]On-screen, Margaret places a hand over his and says, “Then I’ll help you expose every last one of them.”[/i]
: [i]On-screen, the false humans appear in a secret underground ballroom, all laughing villainously while drinking stolen memories from crystal glasses.[/i]
: [i]One says they “despise real human warmth” and another kicks a puppy-shaped service drone.[/i]
: [i]Margaret discovers her corporate job has been secretly polishing false-human reputations through planted memories.[/i]
: [i]Her boss calls and demands she return to the city. Krys asks whether she’ll choose her career or “the truth in her heart.”[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: That is a terrible thing to ask someone you’ve known for three days.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Two and a half, technically.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Worse.
<<clear_portrait YarnManager>>
: [i]On-screen, Margaret throws her work badge into the ocean, kisses Krys, and declares that love is the strongest Fate of all.[/i]
: [i]Together, they expose the false humans, save the town, and reopen the family shop as a Hunter support center.[/i]
: [i]The movie ends on a freeze-frame of Margaret and Krys laughing under fireworks.[/i]
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Well. That was something.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: It definitely was.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: What did you think?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Very ridiculous, but fun. I liked Margaret’s parents, and some of the jokes were cute.
Eve: The romance was rushed. They should’ve spent more time showing why Margaret and Krys actually liked each other, instead of just having him look sad in the rain.
Eve: Anyway, the weapon repair scene was the real crime.
<<set_portrait YarnManager Cyrus>>
Cyrus: Worse than the puppy drone?
<<set_portrait YarnManager Eve>>
Eve: Much worse. That rifle deserved justice.
===


